eid shows, we can reduce income inequality and create a pool of qualified, competent home health care providers who would contribute to the well-being of us all. The Caring Class also serves as a guide into the world of our home health care system. Nearly 50 million US families look after an elderly or disabled loved one. This book explains the issues and choices they face. Schweid explores the narratives, histories, and people behind home health care in the United States, examining how we might improve the lives of both those who receive care and those who provide it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHome care serviceszNew York (State)zNew York. 0aHome health aidesxTraining ofzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aHome health aideszNew York (State)zNew York. 0aOlder peoplexHome carezNew York (State)zNew York. 4aConsumer Health & Fitness. 4aDiscrimination & Race Relations. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh  aHealth Care Cooperatives, Geriatric care, Home Health Aides pay, caring for elderly family members.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073908408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2021 Englishz978311075417908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2021z9783110753943oZDB-23-PLW40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501754128?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501754128423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501754128/original  a978-3-11-073908-4  Cornell University Press Complet